# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alexander-fleming
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alexander-fleming/100-greatest-britons] One of the more controversial figures to be included on the list was the occultist Aleister Crowley which Helen Haste saw as an example of British eccentricity.
[src:alexander-fleming/100-greatest-britons] The poll and advocacy model of the final programme prevented the top ten figures from receiving critical scrutiny and the result was hagiographic.
[src:alexander-fleming/100-greatest-britons] The Controller of BBC Two, Jane Root, said she hoped the list would produce "plenty of debate".
[src:alexander-fleming/100-greatest-britons] However, the resulting television show left many controversies of its subjects unaddressed.
[src:alexander-fleming/100-greatest-britons] Two Irish nationals, Bono from U2 and Bob Geldof were included.
[src:alexander-fleming/100-greatest-britons] Sir Ernest Shackleton and Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington, were both Anglo-Irish in what is now the Republic of Ireland when all of Ireland was part of the United Kingdom, and Alexander Fleming in 20th place was Scottish.
[src:alexander-fleming/100-greatest-britons] There are nine Scottish people on the list and thirteen of the 100 are women.
[src:alexander-fleming/100-greatest-britons] Only one entry was from the BAME community, (Freddie Mercury).
[src:alexander-fleming/100-greatest-britons] Four of the list are Welsh: Owain Glyndŵr, Aneurin Bevan, Richard Burton, David Lloyd George.
[src:alexander-fleming/100-greatest-britons] Two of the list are pre-English, (Boudica, King Arthur).
[src:alexander-fleming/100-greatest-britons] The highest-ranked living person was Margaret Thatcher, placed 16th.
[src:alexander-fleming/100-greatest-britons] Ringo Starr was the only member of the Beatles not on the list.
[src:alexander-fleming/100-greatest-britons] Isambard Kingdom Brunel occupied the top spot in the polls for some time due largely to "students from Brunel University who have been campaigning vigorously for the engineer for weeks." However, a late surge in the final week of voting put Winston Churchill into first place.
[src:alexander-fleming/100-greatest-britons] Although the BBC's original ranked list has been removed from their web server and what remains is only an alphabetical list of the Top 100, several other sources have preserved the original ranked list.
[src:alexander-fleming/100-greatest-britons] There was some question as to whether the Richard Burton listed at No.
[src:alexander-fleming/100-greatest-britons] A BBC press release makes clear that the actor was intended.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] Lucila Godoy Alcayaga borrowed the pseudonym, Gabriela Mistral, from her favorite poets, Gabriele D'Annunzio and Frédéric Mistral.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] Her poetry is distinguished by intense emotion and straightforward language, having been influenced also by the modernist movement.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] Affection, deceit, sorrow, nature, travel, and love for children are some of their major themes.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] Mistral's first prominent poetry collection was *Desolación* ("Despair"), published in 1922.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] *Ternura* ("Tenderness"), published in 1924, contains nursery rhymes and lullabies for children whereas *Tala* ("Harvesting", 1938) makes use of strange imagery and free verse.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] She was well-known for writing op-eds for major Chilean newspapers such as *El Coquimbo: Diario Radical* and *La Voz de Elqui*.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] In her country, she became the first female to be awarded the National Prize for Literature.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] Mistral received eight nominations beginning in 1940.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] For 1945, she was nominated by the newly inducted Swedish Academy member Elin Wägner (1882–1949) by which she was eventually awarded.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] In total, the Nobel Committee received 27 nominations for 22 writers.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] Five of the nominees were nominated first-time: Thomas Stearns Eliot (awarded in 1948), Yiorgos Theotokas, Edward Morgan Forster, and Marie Under.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] There were five female nominees namely Elisaveta Bagryana, Maria Madalena de Martel Patrício, Gabriela Mistral, Henriette Charasson and Marie Under.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] The nominations of the Armando Alvares Pedroso, Henriette Charasson, Teixeira de Pascoaes and Enrique Larreta were declared invalid by the Nobel Committee.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] The French poet Paul Valéry was nominated for the tenth, eleventh and twelfth time by three members of the Swedish Academy.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] It is believed that the Academy intended to award Valéry the prize in 1945, but he died in July.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] The authors Maurice Baring, Ursula Bethell, Robert Brasillach, Dietrich Bonhoeffer, Ernst Cassirer, Mário de Andrade, Margaret Deland, Lucie Delarue-Mardrus, Robert Desnos, Jelena Dimitrijević, Pierre Drieu La Rochelle, Maurice Donnay, Alfred Douglas, E.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] Eddison, Ioan Constantin Filitti, Zinaida Gippius, Ellen Glasgow, Josef Hora, Else Lasker-Schüler, Régis Messac, Arthur Morrison, Otto Neurath, Kitaro Nishida, Charles Gilman Norris, Maria Pawlikowska-Jasnorzewska, Alexander Roda Roda, Felix Salten, Lurana W.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] Sheldon, Antal Szerb, Aleksey Nikolayevich Tolstoy, Charles Williams, Emmanuel Bove died in 1945 without having been nominated for the prize.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] The Dutch historian Johan Huizinga and Austrian-Bohemian author Franz Werfel died months before the announcement.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] Gabriela Mistral had been proposed several times by the Nobel committee of the Swedish Academy since 1940 before she was awarded in 1945.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] The Swedish poet and Academy member Hjalmar Gullberg's acclaimed translations of Mistral's poetry is believed to have been a crucial factor for the Academy to award Mistral the prize.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] Three committee members, Fredrik Böök, Anders Österling and Sigfrid Siwertz, initially advocated that the 1945 Nobel Prize in Literature should be awarded to the French poet and essayist Paul Valéry.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] But after Valéry had died during the deliberations that year, Österling and Siwertz dropped their support for the proposal arguing that the Nobel prize should not be awarded posthumously, an opinion that was supported by committee member Hjalmar Hammarskjöld.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] Böök sticked with the propsal to award Valéry, arguing that there were no obstacle for awarding the prize posthumously, as had happened in 1931.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] After initial misgivings that Valéry's work was too esoteric, committee chairman Per Hallström joined Böök's proposal to award Valéry.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] After Valéry had died, Österling and Siwertz supported Hammarskjöld's proposal to award Gabriela Mistral, thus giving Mistral's candidacy the majority of support in the Nobel committee.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] The committee also considered the French author Jules Romains as a contender for the prize, but decided to await further volumes of his novel cycle *Les Hommes de bonne volonté*.
[src:alexander-fleming/1945-nobel-prize-in-literature] Eliot (subsequently awarded the 1948 Nobel Prize in Literature) was rejected by committee chairman Per Hallström: "The extremely exclusive nature of the poetry in question makes it hardly suitable for an award with the Nobel Prize in Literature, which has to answer to a fairly universal forum".
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] The **20th Century Press Archives** (German: *Pressearchiv 20.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert*) comprises about 19 million newspaper clippings, organized in folders about persons, companies, wares, events and topics.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] It originates from the Hamburg Kolonialinstitut (colonial institute) founded in 1908.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] Within the Hamburg Institute of International Economics (HWWA) it turned into a unique public press archive.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] In 2007 it was absorbed by the German National Library of Economics (ZBW) and merged with the Wirtschaftsarchiv (economics archive) of the Kiel Institute for the World Economy (IfW), founded in 1914.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] Article collection was discontinued at the end of 2005, but the archive is still open to the public.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] The archive has its origins in two institutions in the German cities of Hamburg and Kiel.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] In Hamburg, after a few years, the "Zentralstelle" (central office) of the Kolonialinstitut was transformed from a free information center for colonial issues into a comprehensive archive of global political and economic topics, which primarily supported the city's merchants.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] After the breakdown of the German colonial empire in World War I, the renaming to "Hamburgisches Welt-Wirtschafts-Archiv" in 1919 sealed this reorientation.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] The staff of HWWA reflected its importance and grew from 54 in 1919 to 183 permanent or temporary employees in 1958 – a number that seems to have remained largely stable until the late 1990s.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] Founded shortly before the outbreak of the First World War, the Kiel Economic Archive and its library were closely linked to the scientific work of the IfW, which focused on global economic contexts and their practical use.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] In 1966, the library of the IfW was given the function of a central library for economics by the German Research Foundation (DFG) in the Federal Republic of Germany, and in 1993, the department was renamed accordingly.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] During the first and second world wars, both archives were intensively involved in the foreign and wartime planning of the empire and the Nazi state.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] Starting in 1936, "Confidential Reports from the Foreign Press" provided selected economic leaders and Nazi departments with "largely unfiltered information and comments on economic issues from foreign media and represented a unique feature in Nazi media policy".
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] Acting with the informal means of a foreign cultural and information policy supplementing the military expansion policy, HWWA and IfW dedicated their services to the Nazi regime.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] In 1996, a closer cooperation between HWWA and ZBW / Wirtschaftsarchiv began, with the aim of merging the two archives.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] From the beginning of 2001, the articles were indexed according to a new common classification system and made retrievable via a reference database, "EconPress".
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] Following a recommendation from an evaluation within the Leibniz Association in 2003, the current press documentation was finished at the end of 2005 and the materials were frozen at that point.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] The separate existence of the HWWA ended in 2007 with the integration of its press documentation and library into the ZBW as a newly formed foundation under public law.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] Today, the press archive belongs to the (research) organisations of the Leibniz Association.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] By 1919 at the latest, the Hamburg archive collected "press clippings on a global scale".
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] More than 1400 sources were monitored for the press archives.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] Their broad international distribution provides access to the history of political thought and receptive history of the covered topics.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] Occasionally, the collected publications go back as far as 1826.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] While the persons archive was only available in paper form until its partial digitization, the holdings of the topics, wares and companies archives were saved every ten years on roll film or microfiche since the 1960s and then the paper clippings were pulped.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] The holdings of the Kiel Wirtschaftsarchiv are less comprehensively documented.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] The "war archive" of 1914–1918, which amounted to one million clippings, was destroyed by a bomb strike in 1942.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] In 1958, when six scientific experts and more than 30 employees in total were collecting and organizing the material, the total extent of the archive was estimated as more than three million, and in 1993 as more than ten million.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert* application, parts of the holdings of both archives are now accessible on the web.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] From 2004 to 2007, the German Research Foundation funded a project to digitize parts of the archives, namely the materials from the beginning up to 1949 (the formation of the Federal Republic of Germany).
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] The paper clippings from the folders of the persons archive were scanned, and metadata (folder and document ID as well as page number, occasionally also source, publication date, author and title) were recorded by project staff.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] Optical character recognition could not be applied due to the partially used Fraktur scripts, the constantly changing fonts (as well as languages) in the sequence of the articles, and the sometimes poor quality of the clippings.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] However, the approximately 5,500 person folders created before 1949 are fully accessible online.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] The roll film parts of the archive (up to 1960) have also been digitized.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] As neither the folders nor the documents on these films were separated in a machine-readable fashion, such formal elements could not be automatically derived.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] Instead, the pages had to be "sliced" with specially developed "Slider" software, assembled into documents and folders, and given metadata.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] Only a small part of this labor-intensive process was finished at the end of the project in 2007.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] It is continued today, so that new folders are continually made available via the web application "Pressemappe 20.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert", which was created within the framework of the project.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] 11,000 company folders on digitized roll film, by 2018 about 7,500 were accessible online.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] For the topics and wares archives, the proportion of online folders seems to be significantly lower.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] The persons are alphabetically indexed by name, while the companies are accessible by name, geographically by their headquarters and via industry lists.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] The topics can be accessed via the topics hierarchy and country system as well as through a search for subject and geographical GND keywords, and via a world map with geolocations.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] The limitation to 1949 was made for capacity reasons, and due to intellectual property rights restrictions.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] Numerous individual articles within the dossiers are subject to blocking notices if the death of the author (or in the case of anonymous or pseudonymous works, the date of publication) is less than 70 years ago.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] With a moving wall more and more documents should be released over time.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] How many of the about 5.7 million documents digitized in the context of the project are accessible to the scientific and general public on the web is not known.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] In 2019, the German National Library of Economics (ZBW) placed all the metadata of the archives under a CC0 licence, and began a cooperation and "data donation" with Wikimedia Deutschland.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] This led to the creation of many new Wikidata items and the enrichment of many existing items; by the end of 2022, every folder in the archive was connected to items in Wikidata.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] In 2024, changes to intellectual property rights in Europe made it possible to provide complete digitized images from the archive – some 3.8 million pages – for online viewing within the European Union.
[src:alexander-fleming/20th-century-press-archives] A volunteer project is working on adding links to the archive's folders in Wikidata, so that Wikidata provides an index to the material.
[src:alexander-fleming/91006-fleming-p01] The following is a partial list of minor planets, running from minor-planet number 91001 through 92000, inclusive.
[src:alexander-fleming/91006-fleming-p01] The primary data for this and other partial lists is based on JPL's "Small-Body Orbital Elements" and data available from the Minor Planet Center.
[src:alexander-fleming/91006-fleming-p01] Critical list information is also provided by the MPC, unless otherwise specified from Lowell Observatory.
[src:alexander-fleming/91006-fleming-p01] A detailed description of the table's columns and additional sources are given on the main page including a complete list of every page in this series, and a statistical break-up on the dynamical classification of minor planets.
[src:alexander-fleming/91006-fleming-p01] Also see the summary list of all named bodies in numerical and alphabetical order, and the corresponding naming citations for the number range of this particular list.
[src:alexander-fleming/91006-fleming-p01] New namings may only be added to this list after official publication, as the preannouncement of names is condemned by the Working Group for Small Bodies Nomenclature of the International Astronomical Union.
[src:alexander-fleming/actonian-prize] Each year the prize was to be awarded, announcements were published, and competitors for the prize were requested to send their essays to the Secretary of Royal Institution, Albemarle Street, London, and adjudication was made by the managers and announced a few months later.
[src:alexander-fleming/actonian-prize] The prize was named for Hannah Acton who in 1838 left £1,000 to the Royal Institution in memory of her husband, the architect Samuel Acton, the income from which was to be spent for prizes for the best essay on the beneficence of the Almighty, as illustrative of a department of science.
[src:alexander-fleming/actonian-prize] The Royal Institution's Actonian Prize is now given to an invited lecturer and is not competitive.
[src:alexander-fleming/actonian-prize] The first prize of one hundred guineas was awarded to George Fownes for his *Chemistry as Exemplifies the Wisdom and Beneficence of God* published in 1844.
[src:alexander-fleming/actonian-prize] At the time, he was the chemical lecturer at Middlesex Hospital.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] An **agar plate** is a Petri dish that contains a growth medium solidified with agar, used to culture microorganisms.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] Sometimes selective compounds are added to influence growth, such as antibiotics.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] Individual microorganisms placed on the plate will grow into individual colonies, each a clone genetically identical to the individual ancestor organism (except for the low, unavoidable rate of mutation).
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] Thus, the plate can be used either to estimate the concentration of organisms in a liquid culture or a suitable dilution of that culture using a colony counter, or to generate genetically pure cultures from a mixed culture of genetically different organisms.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] Several methods are available to plate out cells.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] In this technique, a drop of the culture on the end of a thin, sterile loop of wire, sometimes known as an inoculator, is streaked across the surface of the agar leaving organisms behind, a higher number at the beginning of the streak and a lower number at the end.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] At some point during a successful "streak", the number of organisms deposited will be such that distinct individual colonies will grow in that area which may be removed for further culturing, using another sterile loop.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] Another way of plating organisms, next to streaking, on agar plates is the spot analysis.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] This type of analysis is often used to check the viability of cells and is performed with pinners (often also called froggers).
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] A third technique is using sterile glass beads to plate out cells.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] In this technique, cells are grown in a liquid culture, in which a small volume is pipetted on the agar plate and then spread out with the beads.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] Replica plating is another technique used to plate out cells on agar plates.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] These four techniques are the most common, but others are also possible.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] It is crucial to work in a sterile manner to prevent contamination on the agar plates.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] Plating is thus often done in a laminar flow cabinet or on the working bench next to a bunsen burner.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] In 1881, Fanny Hesse, who was working as a technician for her husband Walther Hesse in the laboratory of Robert Koch, suggested agar as an effective setting agent, since it had been commonplace in jam making for some time.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] Agar plates may be formulated as either permissive, with the intent of allowing the growth of whatever organisms are present, or restrictive or selective, with the intent of only allowing the growth of a particular subset of those organisms.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] This correlates to some degree with defined and undefined media; undefined media, made from natural products and containing an unknown combination of very many organic molecules, is typically more permissive in terms of supplying the needs of a wider variety of organisms.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] In contrast, defined media can be precisely tailored to select organisms with specific properties.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] Agar plates may also be indicator plates, in which the organisms are not selected based on growth, but are instead distinguished by a color change in some colonies, typically caused by the action of an enzyme on some compound added to the medium.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] The plates are incubated for 12 hours up to several days, depending on the test that is performed.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] Blood agar plates (BAPs) contain mammalian blood (usually sheep or horse), typically at a 5–10% concentration.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] BAPs are enriched, and differential media is used to isolate fastidious organisms and detect hemolytic activity. β-Hemolytic activity will show lysis and complete digestion of red blood cell contents surrounding a colony.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] Examples include *Streptococcus haemolyticus*. α-Hemolysis will only cause partial lysis of the red blood cells (the cell membrane is left intact) and appear green or brown due to the conversion of hemoglobin to methemoglobin.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] An example of this would be *Streptococcus viridans*. γ-Hemolysis (or non-hemolytic) is the term referring to a lack of hemolytic activity.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] BAPs also contain meat extract or yeast extract, tryptone, sodium chloride, and agar.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] Chocolate agar is a type of blood agar plate in which the blood cells have been lysed by heating the cells to 80 °C.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] It is used for growing fastidious respiratory bacteria, such as *Haemophilus influenzae*.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] Chocolate agar is named for its color, and no chocolate is contained in the plate.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] Thayer–Martin agar is a chocolate agar designed to isolate *Neisseria gonorrhoeae* and *Neisseria meningitidis*.
[src:alexander-fleming/agar-plates] Thiosulfate–citrate–bile salts–sucrose agar enhances growth of *Vibrio* spp., including *Vibrio cholerae*.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Hodgkin was born in Banbury, Oxfordshire, on 5 February 1914.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] He was the oldest of three sons of Quakers George Hodgkin and Mary Wilson Hodgkin.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] His father was the son of Thomas Hodgkin and had read for the Natural Science Tripos at Cambridge where he had befriended electrophysiologist Keith Lucas.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Because of poor eyesight, he was unable to study medicine and eventually ended up working for a bank in Banbury.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] As members of the Society of Friends, George and Mary opposed the Military Service Act of 1916, which introduced conscription, and had to endure a great deal of abuse from their local community, including an attempt to throw George in one of the town canals.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] In 1916, George Hodgkin travelled to Armenia as part of an investigation of distress.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Moved by the misery and suffering of Armenian refugees he attempted to go back there in 1918 on a route through the Persian Gulf (as the northern route was closed because of the October Revolution in Russia).
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] He died of dysentery in Baghdad on 24 June 1918, just a few weeks after his youngest son, Keith, had been born.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] From an early life on, Hodgkin and his brothers were encouraged to explore the country around their home, which instilled in Alan an interest in natural history, particularly ornithology.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] At the age of 15, he helped Wilfred Backhouse Alexander with surveys of heronries and later, at Gresham's School, he overlapped and spent a lot of time with David Lack.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] In 1930, he was the winner of a bronze medal in the Public Schools Essay Competition organised by the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Alan started his education at The Downs School where his contemporaries included future scientists Frederick Sanger, Alec Bangham, "neither outstandingly brilliant at school" according to Hodgkin, as well as future artists Lawrence Gowing and Kenneth Rowntree.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] After the Downs School, he went on to Gresham's School where he overlapped with future composer Benjamin Britten as well as Maury Meiklejohn.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] He ended up receiving a scholarship at Trinity College, Cambridge in botany, zoology and chemistry.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Between school and college, he spent May 1932 at the Freshwater Biological Station at Wray Castle based on a recommendation of his future Director of Studies at Trinity, Carl Pantin.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Smith, whose daughter Dorothy was also married to Alan's uncle Robert Howard Hodgkin.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] In the autumn of 1932, Hodgkin started as a freshman scholar at Trinity College where his friends included classicists John Raven and Michael Grant, fellow-scientists Richard Synge and John H.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Humphrey, as well as Polly and David Hill, the children of Nobel laureate Archibald Hill.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] He took physiology with chemistry and zoology for the first two years, including lectures by Nobel laureate E.D.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] For Part II of the tripos he decided to focus on physiology instead of zoology.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Nevertheless, he participated in a zoological expedition to the Atlas Mountains in Morocco led by John Pringle in 1934.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] He finished Part II of the tripos in July 1935 and stayed at Trinity as a research fellow.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] During his studies, Hodgkin, who described himself as "having been brought up as a supporter of the British Labour Party" was friends with communists and actively participated in the distribution of anti-war pamphlets.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] At Cambridge, he knew James Klugmann and John Cornford, but he emphasised in his autobiography that none of his friends "made any serious effort to convert me [to Communism], either then or later." From 1935 to 1937, Hodgkin was a member of the Cambridge Apostles.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Hodgkin started conducting experiments on how electrical activity is transmitted in the sciatic nerve of frogs in July 1934.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] He found that a nerve impulse arriving at a cold or compression block, can decrease the electrical threshold beyond the block, suggesting that the impulse produces a spread of an electrotonic potential in the nerve beyond the block.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] In 1936, Hodgkin was invited by Herbert Gasser, then director of the Rockefeller Institute in New York City, to work in his laboratory during 1937–38.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] There he met Rafael Lorente de Nó and Kenneth Stewart Cole with whom he ended up publishing a paper.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] During that year he also spent time at the Woods Hole Marine Biological Laboratory where he was introduced to the squid giant axon, which ended up being the model system with which he conducted most of the research that eventually led to his Nobel Prize.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] In the spring of 1938, he visited Joseph Erlanger at Washington University in St.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Louis who told him he would take Hodgkin's local circuit theory of nerve impulse propagation seriously if he could show that altering the resistance of the fluid outside a nerve fibre made a difference to the velocity of nerve impulse conduction.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Working with single nerve fibres from shore crabs and squids, he showed that the conduction rate was much faster in seawater than in oil, providing strong evidence for the local circuit theory.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] After his return to Cambridge he started collaborating with Andrew Huxley who had entered Trinity as a freshman in 1935, three years after Hodgkin.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] With a £300 equipment grant from the Rockefeller Foundation, Hodgkin managed to set up a similar physiology setup to the one he had worked with at the Rockefeller Institute.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] He moved all his equipment to the Plymouth Marine Laboratory in July 1939.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] There, he and Huxley managed to insert a fine cannula into the giant axon of squids and record action potentials from inside the nerve fibre.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] They sent a short note of their success to *Nature* just before the outbreak of World War II.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Despite his Quaker upbringing, Hodgkin was eager to join the war effort as contact with the Nazis during his stay in Germany in 1932 had removed all his pacifist beliefs.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] His first post was at the Royal Aircraft Establishment where he worked on issues in aviation medicine, such as oxygen supply for pilots at high altitudes and the decompression sickness caused by nitrogen bubbles coming out of the blood.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] In February 1940 he transferred to the Telecommunications Research Establishment (TRE) where he worked on the development of centimetric radar, including the design of the village Inn AGLT airborne gun-laying system.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Bowen's group in St Athan in South Wales and lived in a local guest house together with John Pringle and Robert Hanbury Brown.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] The group moved to Swanage in May 1940 where Pringle replaced Bowen as leader of the group.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] In March 1941, Hodgkin flew on the test flight of a Bristol Blenheim fitted with the first airborne centimetric radar system.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] In February and March 1944, he visited the MIT Radiation Laboratory to help foster the interchange of information on developments in radar between Britain and America.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Providing a readable account of the little-known piece of military history that he was a part of during World War II was a main motivation for Hodgkin to write his autobiography *Chance and Design: Reminiscences of Science in Peace and War*.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] As the Allied Forces' invasion of France and their continued advance towards Germany in autumn 1944 suggested an end of the war in the foreseeable future, Hodgkin started to plan his return to a career in research at Cambridge.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Rushton and they published an article on how to calculate a nerve fibre's membrane resistance, membrane capacity, its axoplasm's resistance, and the resistance of the external fluid in which the fibre is placed, from experimental observations.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] After being released from military service in August 1945 upon Adrian's request, Hodgkin was able to restart his experiments in collaboration with Bernard Katz and his pre-war collaborator Andrew Huxley.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] They spent the summers of 1947, 1948, and 1949 at the Plymouth Marine Laboratory where they continued to measure resting and action potentials from inside the giant axon of the squid.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Together with Katz, he provided evidence that the permeability of the neuronal cell membrane for sodium increased during an action potential, thus allowing sodium ions to diffuse inward.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] The data they had obtained in 1949 resulted in a series of five papers published in *The Journal of Physiology* that described what became later known as the Hodgkin–Huxley model of the action potential and eventually earned Hodgkin and Huxley the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Cole they used a technique of electrophysiology, known as the *voltage clamp* to measure ionic currents through the membranes of squid axons while holding the membrane voltage at a set level.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] They proposed that the characteristic shape of the action potential is caused by changes in the selective permeability of the membrane for different ions, specifically sodium, potassium, and chloride.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] A model that relies on a set of differential equations and describes each component of an excitable cell as an electrical element was in good agreement with their empirical measurements.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] The cell membrane depolarisation sequence where a small depolarization leads to an increase in sodium permeability, which leads to influx of sodium ions, which in turn depolarizes the membrane even more is now known as the Hodgkin cycle.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] In addition, Hodgkin and Huxley's findings led them to hypothesize the existence of ion channels on cell membranes, which were confirmed only decades later.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Confirmation of ion channels came with the development of the patch clamp leading to a Nobel prize in 1991 for Erwin Neher and Bert Sakmann, and in 2003 for Roderick MacKinnon.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] After establishing ion movements across a selectively permeable cell membrane as the mechanism of the action potential, Hodgkin turned his attention to how the ionic interchange that occurs during the action potential could be reversed afterwards.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Together with Richard Keynes he demonstrated that in addition to the changes in permeability that lead to an action potential, there is a secretory mechanism that ejects sodium and absorbs potassium against the electrochemical gradients.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] A few years later, the Danish scientist Jens Christian Skou discovered the enzyme Na+/K+-ATPase that uses ATP to export three sodium ions in exchange for two potassium ions that are imported, for which he received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1997.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Hodgkin was nominated for the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1953 by Lord Adrian.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] In October 1961, he was told by Swedish journalists that he, Huxley, and Eccles had been awarded the Nobel Prize.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] This turned out to be a false alarm, however, when shortly thereafter it was announced that the 1961 Prize was awarded to Georg von Békésy.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] It was only two years later that Hodgkin, Huxley, and Eccles were finally awarded the Prize "for their discoveries concerning the ionic mechanisms involved in excitation and inhibition in the peripheral and central portions of the nerve cell membrane".
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] During the Nobel Banquet on 10 December 1963, Hodgkin gave the traditional speech on behalf of the three neurophysiologists, thanking the king and the Nobel Committee for Physiology or Medicine for the award.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Incidentally, Hodgkin and his wife attended the Nobel Prize ceremony a second time, three years later, when Hodgkin's father-in-law, Francis Peyton Rous, was awarded the 1966 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] From 1951 to 1969, Hodgkin was the Foulerton Professor of the Royal Society at Cambridge.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] In 1970 he became the John Humphrey Plummer Professor of Biophysics at Cambridge.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Around this time he also ended his experiments on nerve at the Plymouth Marine Laboratory and switched his focus to visual research which he could do in Cambridge with the help of others while serving as president of the Royal Society.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Together with Denis Baylor and Peter Detwiler he published a series of papers on turtle photoreceptors.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] From 1970 to 1975 Hodgkin served as the 53rd president of the Royal Society (PRS).
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] During his tenure as PRS, he was knighted in 1972 and admitted into the Order of Merit in 1973.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] From 1978 to 1985 he was the 34th Master of Trinity College, Cambridge.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] He served on the Royal Society Council from 1958 to 1960 and on the Medical Research Council from 1959 to 1963.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] He was foreign secretary of the Physiological Society from 1961 to 1967.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] A portrait of Hodgkin by Michael Noakes hangs in Trinity College's collection.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] During his stay at the Rockefeller Institute in 1937, Hodgkin got to know the American pathologist Francis Peyton Rous who was later awarded the 1966 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] When Rous invited him for dinner to his home, Hodgkin got to know Rous' daughter, Marni, who was then a student at Swarthmore College.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] He proposed to her before going back to England in 1938, but she rejected him.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] When Hodgkin briefly returned to the US in 1944 (see Wartime activities), they reunited and got married on 31 March.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Their first daughter, Sarah, was born in April 1945, shortly before the Hodgkins moved back to Cambridge.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] They had three more children: Deborah Hodgkin (born 2 May 1947), Jonathan Hodgkin (born 24 August 1949), and Rachel Hodgkin (born June 1951).
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Marni became a Children's Book Editor at Macmillan Publishing Company and a successful writer of children's literature, including *Young Winter's Tales* and *Dead Indeed*.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Jonathan Hodgkin became a molecular biologist at Cambridge University.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Deborah Hodgkin is also a successful psychologist.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Thomas Hodgkin (1798–1866), who first described Hodgkin's lymphoma, was Alan Hodgkin's great-uncle.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] Hodgkin suffered from a series of medical problems that began soon after his retirement as Master of Trinity.
[src:alexander-fleming/alan-hodgkin] In 1989 he had surgery to relieve pressure on the spinal cord from one of the intervertebral discs in his neck, which left him unable to walk without support, and with progressive disablement.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] He also discovered the enzyme lysozyme from his nasal discharge in 1922, and along with it a bacterium he named *Micrococcus lysodeikticus*, later renamed *Micrococcus luteus*.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Fleming was knighted for his scientific achievements in 1944.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] In 1999, he was named in *Time* magazine's list of the 100 Most Important People of the 20th century.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] In 2002, he was included in the BBC's television poll of the *100 Greatest Britons*, and in 2009, he was also voted third "greatest Scot" in an opinion poll conducted by STV, behind only Robert Burns and William Wallace.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Born on 6 August 1881 at Lochfield farm near Darvel, in Ayrshire, Scotland, Alexander Fleming was the third of four children of farmer Hugh Fleming and Grace Stirling Morton, the daughter of a neighbouring farmer.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Hugh Fleming had four surviving children from his first marriage.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] He was 59 at the time of his second marriage to Grace, and died when Alexander was seven.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Fleming went to Loudoun Moor School and Darvel School, and earned a two-year scholarship to Kilmarnock Academy before moving to London, where he attended the Royal Polytechnic Institution.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] After working in a shipping office for four years, the twenty-year-old Alexander Fleming inherited some money from an uncle, John Fleming.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] His elder brother, Tom, was already a physician and suggested that he should follow the same career.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] In 1901, the younger Alexander enrolled at St Mary's Hospital Medical School in Paddington, now part of Imperial College London.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] In 1906, he qualified with an MBBS degree from the school with distinction.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Fleming, who was a private in the London Scottish Regiment of the Volunteer Force from 1900 to 1914, had been a member of the rifle club at the medical school.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] The captain of the club, wishing to retain Fleming in the team, suggested that he join the research department at St Mary's, where he became assistant bacteriologist to Sir Almroth Wright, a pioneer in vaccine therapy and immunology.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] In 1908, he gained a BSc degree with gold medal in bacteriology, and became a lecturer at St Mary's until 1914.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Commissioned lieutenant in 1914 and promoted captain in 1917, Fleming served throughout World War I in the Royal Army Medical Corps, and was Mentioned in Dispatches.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] He and many of his colleagues worked in battlefield hospitals at the Western Front in France.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] In 1918 he returned to St Mary's Hospital, where he was elected Professor of Bacteriology of the University of London in 1928.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] During World War I, Fleming with Leonard Colebrook and Sir Almroth Wright joined the war efforts and practically moved the entire Inoculation Department of St Mary's to the British military hospital at Boulogne-sur-Mer.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Serving as a temporary lieutenant of the Royal Army Medical Corps, he witnessed the death of many soldiers from sepsis resulting from infected wounds.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Antiseptics, which were used at the time to treat infected wounds, he observed, often worsened the injuries.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] In a 1917 article published in the medical journal *The Lancet*, he described an ingenious experiment, which he was able to conduct as a result of his own glassblowing skills, in which he explained why antiseptics were killing more soldiers than infection itself during the war.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Wright strongly supported Fleming's findings, but despite this, most army physicians over the course of the war continued to use antiseptics even in cases where this worsened the condition of the patients.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] At St Mary's Hospital, Fleming continued his investigations into bacteria culture and antibacterial substances.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Allison recalled, Fleming was not a tidy researcher and usually expected unusual bacterial growths in his culture plates.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] In late 1921, while Fleming was maintaining agar plates for bacteria, he found that one of the plates was contaminated with bacteria from the air.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] When he added nasal mucus, he found that the mucus inhibited the bacterial growth.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Surrounding the mucus area was a clear transparent circle (1 cm from the mucus), indicating the killing zone of bacteria, followed by a glassy and translucent ring beyond which was an opaque area indicating normal bacterial growth.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] In the next test, he used bacteria maintained in saline that formed a yellow suspension.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Within two minutes of adding fresh mucus, the yellow saline turned completely clear.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] He extended his tests using tears, which were contributed by his co-workers.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] As Allison reminisced, saying, "For the next five or six weeks, our tears were the source of supply for this extraordinary phenomenon.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Many were the lemons we used (after the failure of onions) to produce a flow of tears...
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] His further tests with sputum, cartilage, blood, semen, ovarian cyst fluid, pus, and egg white showed that the bactericidal agent was present in all of these.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] This was the first recorded discovery of lysozyme.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] With Allison, he published further studies on lysozyme in October issue of the *British Journal of Experimental Pathology* the same year.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Although he was able to obtain larger amounts of lysozyme from egg whites, the enzyme was only effective against small counts of harmless bacteria, and therefore had little therapeutic potential.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] This indicates one of the major differences between pathogenic and harmless bacteria.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Described in the original publication, "a patient suffering from acute coryza" was later identified as Fleming himself.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] He also identified the bacterium present in the nasal mucus as *Micrococcus lysodeikticus*, giving the species name (meaning "lysis indicator" for its susceptibility to lysozymal activity).
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] The species was reassigned as *Micrococcus luteus* in 1972.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] The "Fleming strain" (NCTC2665) of this bacterium has become a model in different biological studies.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] By 1927, Fleming had been investigating the properties of staphylococci.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] He was already well known from his earlier work, and had developed a reputation as a brilliant researcher.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] In 1928, he studied the variation of *Staphylococcus aureus* grown under natural condition, after the work of Joseph Warwick Bigger, who discovered that the bacterium could grow into a variety of types (strains).
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] On 3 September 1928, Fleming returned to his laboratory having spent a holiday with his family at Suffolk.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Before leaving for his holiday, he inoculated staphylococci on culture plates and left them on a bench in a corner of his laboratory.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] On his return, Fleming noticed that one culture was contaminated with a fungus, and that the colonies of staphylococci immediately surrounding the fungus had been destroyed, whereas other staphylococci colonies farther away were normal, famously remarking "That's funny".
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Fleming showed the contaminated culture to his former assistant Merlin Pryce, who reminded him, "That's how you discovered lysozyme." He identified the mould as being from the genus *Penicillium.* He suspected it to be *P. chrysogenum,* but a colleague Charles J.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] La Touche identified it as *P. rubrum.* It was later corrected as *P. notatum* and then officially accepted as *P. chrysogenum*.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] The laboratory in which Fleming discovered and tested penicillin is preserved as the Alexander Fleming Laboratory Museum in St.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] The source of the fungal contaminant was established in 1966 as coming from La Touche's room, which was directly below Fleming's.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Fleming grew the mould in a pure culture and found that the culture broth contained an antibacterial substance.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] It also affected *Neisseria gonorrhoeae,* which causes gonorrhoea, although this bacterium is Gram-negative.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] After some months of calling it "mould juice" or "the inhibitor", he gave the name penicillin on 7 March 1929 for the antibacterial substance present in the mould.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Fleming presented his discovery on 13 February 1929 before the Medical Research Club.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] His talk on "A medium for the isolation of Pfeiffer's bacillus" did not receive any particular attention or comment.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Henry Dale, the then Director of National Institute for Medical Research and chair of the meeting, much later reminisced that he did not even sense any striking point of importance in Fleming's speech.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Fleming published his discovery in 1929 in the *British Journal of Experimental Pathology,* but little attention was paid to the article.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] His problem was the difficulty of producing penicillin in large amounts, and moreover, isolation of the main compound.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Even with the help of Harold Raistrick and his team of biochemists at the London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine, chemical purification was futile.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] "As a result, penicillin languished largely forgotten in the 1930s", as Milton Wainwright described.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] As late as in 1936, there was no appreciation for penicillin.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] When Fleming talked of its medical importance at the Second International Congress of Microbiology held in London, no one believed him.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] In Oxford, Ernst Chain and Edward Abraham were studying the molecular structure of the antibiotic.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Abraham was the first to propose the correct structure of penicillin.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Shortly after the team published its first results in 1940, Fleming telephoned Howard Florey, Chain's head of department, to say that he would be visiting within the next few days.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] When Chain heard that Fleming was coming, he remarked "Good God!
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Norman Heatley suggested transferring the active ingredient of penicillin back into water by changing its acidity.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] This produced enough of the drug to begin testing on animals.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] There were many more people involved in the Oxford team, and at one point the entire Sir William Dunn School of Pathology was involved in its production.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] After the team had developed a method of purifying penicillin to an effective first stable form in 1940, several clinical trials ensued, and their amazing success inspired the team to develop methods for mass production and mass distribution in 1945.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Fleming was modest about his part in the development of penicillin, describing his fame as the "Fleming Myth" and he praised Florey and Chain for transforming the laboratory curiosity into a practical drug.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Fleming was the first to discover the properties of the active substance, giving him the privilege of naming it: penicillin.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] He also kept, grew, and distributed the original mould for twelve years, and continued until 1940 to try to get help from any chemist who had enough skill to make penicillin.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Sir Henry Harris summed up the process in 1998 as: "Without Fleming, no Chain; without Chain, no Florey; without Florey, no Heatley; without Heatley, no penicillin." The discovery of penicillin and its subsequent development as a prescription drug mark the start of modern antibiotics.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] In his first clinical trial, Fleming treated his research scholar Stuart Craddock who had developed severe infection of the nasal antrum (sinusitis).
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] The treatment started on 9 January 1929 but without any effect.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] It probably was due to the fact that the infection was with influenza bacillus (*Haemophilus influenzae*), the bacterium which he had found unsusceptible to penicillin.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Fleming gave some of his original penicillin samples to his colleague-surgeon Arthur Dickson Wright for clinical test in 1928.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Although Wright reportedly said that it "seemed to work satisfactorily", there are no records of its specific use.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Cecil George Paine, a pathologist at the Royal Infirmary in Sheffield and former student of Fleming, was the first to use penicillin successfully for medical treatment.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] He cured eye infections (conjunctivitis) of one adult and three infants (neonatal conjunctivitis) on 25 November 1930.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Fleming also successfully treated severe conjunctivitis in 1932.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Keith Bernard Rogers, who had joined St Mary's as medical student in 1929, was captain of the London University rifle team and was about to participate in an inter-hospital rifle shooting competition when he developed conjunctivitis.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Fleming applied his penicillin and cured Rogers before the competition.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] It is said that the "penicillin worked and the match was won." However, the report that "Keith was probably the first patient to be treated clinically with penicillin ointment" is no longer true as Paine's medical records showed up.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] There is a popular assertion both in popular and scientific literature that Fleming largely abandoned penicillin work in the early 1930s.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] In his review of André Maurois's *The Life of Sir Alexander Fleming, Discoverer of Penicillin,* William L.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Kissick went so far as to say that "Fleming had abandoned penicillin in 1932...
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Although the recipient of many honors and the author of much scientific work, Sir Alexander Fleming does not appear to be an ideal subject for a biography." This is false, as Fleming continued to pursue penicillin research.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] As late as in 1939, Fleming's notebook shows attempts to make better penicillin production using different media.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] In 1941, he published a method for assessment of penicillin effectiveness.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] As to the chemical isolation and purification, Howard Florey and Ernst Chain at the Radcliffe Infirmary in Oxford took up the research to mass-produce it, which they achieved with support from World War II military projects under the British and US governments.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] By mid-1942, the Oxford team produced the pure penicillin compound as yellow powder.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] In August 1942, Harry Lambert (an associate of Fleming's brother Robert) was admitted to St Mary's Hospital due to a life-threatening infection of the nervous system (streptococcal meningitis).
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Fleming treated him with sulphonamides, but Lambert's condition deteriorated.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] He tested the antibiotic susceptibility and found that his penicillin could kill the bacteria.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] At Fleming's request, Florey sent the incompletely purified sample, which Fleming immediately administered into Lambert's spinal canal.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Lambert showed signs of improvement the very next day, and completely recovered within a week.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Fleming published the clinical case in *The Lancet* in 1943.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Upon this medical breakthrough, Allison informed the British Ministry of Health of the importance of penicillin and the need for mass production.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] The War Cabinet was convinced of the usefulness upon which Sir Cecil Weir, Director General of Equipment, called for a meeting on the mode of action on 28 September 1942.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] The Penicillin Committee was created on 5 April 1943.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] The committee consisted of Weir as chairman, Fleming, Florey, Sir Percival Hartley, Allison and representatives from pharmaceutical companies as members.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] The main goals were to produce penicillin rapidly in large quantities with collaboration of American companies, and to supply the drug exclusively for Allied armed forces.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] By D-Day in 1944, enough penicillin had been produced to treat all the wounded of the Allied troops.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Fleming also discovered very early that bacteria developed antibiotic resistance whenever too little penicillin was used or when it was used for too short a period.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Almroth Wright had predicted antibiotic resistance even before it was noticed during experiments.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Fleming cautioned about the use of penicillin in his many speeches around the world.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] On 26 June 1945, he made the following cautionary statements: "the microbes are educated to resist penicillin and a host of penicillin-fast organisms is bred out ...
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] In such cases the thoughtless person playing with penicillin is morally responsible for the death of the man who finally succumbs to infection with the penicillin-resistant organism.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] It had been experimentally shown in 1942 that *S. aureus* could develop penicillin resistance under prolonged exposure.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] It was around that time that the first clinical case of penicillin resistance was reported.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] On 24 December 1915, Fleming married a trained nurse, Sarah Marion McElroy of Killala, County Mayo, Ireland.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Their only child, Robert Fleming (1924–2015), became a general medical practitioner.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] After his first wife's death in 1949, Fleming married Amalia Koutsouri-Vourekas, a Greek colleague at St.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Fleming came from a Presbyterian background, while his first wife Sarah was a (lapsed) Roman Catholic.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] It is said that he was not particularly religious, and their son Robert was later received into the Anglican church, while still reportedly inheriting his two parents' fairly irreligious disposition.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] From 1921 until his death in 1955, Fleming owned a country home named "The Dhoon" in Barton Mills, Suffolk.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] On 11 March 1955, Fleming died at his home in London of a heart attack.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] His ashes are buried in St Paul's Cathedral.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Fleming's discovery of penicillin changed the world of modern medicine by introducing the age of useful antibiotics; penicillin has saved, and is still saving, millions of people around the world.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] The laboratory at St Mary's Hospital where Fleming discovered penicillin is home to the Fleming Museum, a popular London attraction.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] His alma mater, St Mary's Hospital Medical School, merged with Imperial College London in 1988.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] The *Sir Alexander Fleming Building* on the South Kensington campus was opened in 1998, where his son Robert and his great-granddaughter Claire were presented to the Queen; it is now one of the main preclinical teaching sites of the Imperial College School of Medicine.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] His other alma mater, the Royal Polytechnic Institution (now the University of Westminster) has named one of its student halls of residence *Alexander Fleming House*, which is near to Old Street.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] By 1942, penicillin, produced as pure compound, was still in short supply and not available for clinical use.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] When Fleming used the first few samples prepared by the Oxford team to treat Harry Lambert who had streptococcal meningitis, the successful treatment was major news, particularly popularised in *The Times*.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Wright was surprised to discover that Fleming and the Oxford team had not been mentioned, though Oxford was attributed as the source of the drug.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Wright wrote to the editor of *The Times*, which eagerly interviewed Fleming, but Florey prohibited the Oxford team from seeking media coverage.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] As a consequence, only Fleming was widely publicised in the media, which led to the misconception that he was entirely responsible for the discovery and development of the drug.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] The popular story of Winston Churchill's father paying for Fleming's education after Fleming's father saved young Winston from death is false.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] According to the biography, *Penicillin Man: Alexander Fleming and the Antibiotic Revolution* by Kevin Brown, Alexander Fleming, in a letter to his friend and colleague André Gratia, described this as "A wondrous fable." Nor did he save Winston Churchill during World War II.
[src:alexander-fleming/alexander-fleming] Churchill was saved by Lord Moran, using sulphonamides, since he had no experience with penicillin, when Churchill fell ill in Carthage in Tunisia in 1943.
